ew up in the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries entangled households in complex relationships of credit and debt, and one of the most common activities of law courts during the period was debt recovery. Sergeants of the law were empowered to march into debtors’ homes and seize belongings equal in value to the debt owed. These officials were agents of a predatory economy, cogs in a political machinery of state-sponsored plunder.As Daniel Smail shows, the records of medieval European law courts offer some of the most vivid descriptions of material culture in this period, providing insights into the lives of men and women on the cusp of modern capitalism. Then as now, money and value were implicated in questions of power and patterns of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCollecting of accountszFrancezMarseillexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aCollecting of accountszItalyzLuccaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aDebtzFrancezMarseillexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aDebtzItalyzLuccaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMaterial culturezFrancezMarseillexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMaterial culturezItalyzLuccaxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063858540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067497010640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674970106423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674970106.jpg  a978-3-11-063858-5  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles